          "correctOptionId": "opt-2",
          "explanation": "Iodinated contrast agents are a leading cause of AKI. Increased risk is seen in Chronic kidney disease - paicularly diabetic nephropathy The most common clinical course of contrast nephropathy is A rise in SCr beginning 24-48 hours following exposure Peaking within 3-5 days Resolving within 1 week ALSO NOTE: More severe, dialysis-requiring AKI is uncommon Patients with multiple myeloma and renal disease are paicularly susceptible for severe renal failure. Low fractional excretion of sodium and without features of tubular necrosis are common findings. Ref: Harrison-E-18, P-2297."
