          "correctOptionId": "opt-3",
          "explanation": "Heterophil antibodies are present in 50% of children and 90%-95% of adolescents and adults with infectious mononucleosis. Monospot tests are the best diagnostic tools but may not turn positive until the second or third week of the illness. The presence of IgG antibodies by the indirect immunofluorescence test indicates recent or prior EBV infection. IgM antibodies indicate recent infection only. Specific EBV antibodies and cultures are rarely used.",
